# https://www.perplexity.ai/search/please-classify-the-following-qepNM5y2QoanOSHY0x0SyA
	Based on the equipment already owned \u2014 the Kegland Fermzilla 27L Conical Fermenter and the VEVOR 35L Electric Brewing System with pump and mash capabilities \u2014 here is a list of additional essential equipment to start homebrewing effectively:
	Essential Additional Homebrewing Equipment

	    Sanitizer: StarSan or similar food-grade sanitizer to sterilize all equipment that touches the beer after the boil, vital for preventing infection.

	    Hydrometer or Refractometer: For measuring the specific gravity of the wort and beer to monitor fermentation progress and calculate alcohol content.

	    Thermometer: A digital instant-read thermometer to ensure accurate temperature control during pitching yeast and fermentation.

	    Siphon or Auto-Siphon: To transfer beer from the fermenter to bottling or kegging containers without contaminating or oxidizing the beer.

	    Bottling Equipment:

	        Bottling bucket (with spigot) if bottling by hand.

	        Bottle caps and a bottle capper OR swing-top bottles for easy sealing.

	    Bottles: Clean, empty beer bottles suitable for home bottling.

	    Brewing Spoon: Long-handled stainless steel or food-grade plastic spoon for stirring mash and wort.

	    Grain Bag or Strainer: For containing grains or hops during the mash or boil if needed.

	    Priming Sugar: For carbonation if bottling.

	    Wort Chiller: An immersion or counterflow chiller to quickly cool the boiled wort before fermentation, preserving flavor and reducing infection risk.

	    Cleaning Supplies: PBW (Powdered Brewery Wash) or OxiClean Free for thorough cleaning between brews.

	    Measuring Tools: Measuring cup or digital scale for weighing ingredients precisely.

	    Funnels: Food-grade funnels for transferring liquids without spills.

	    Tubing: Food-grade tubing for transferring beer during siphoning.

	With the existing equipment, these additions will cover the entire brewing, fermenting, and packaging process. Optional but helpful tools include a refractometer for gravity measurements, beer thermometer strips for fermentation temperature monitoring, and bottle brushes for cleaning.

	This setup will allow homebrewing a full batch with efficient handling during all stages from mashing, boiling, fermenting to bottling or kegging.